Prime Minister Phan Van Khai assigned the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social Affairs to assist Agent Orange victims by 2000.
The toxic chemical, sprayed by U.S. planes during the Vietnam War, still affects many.
Veterans denied benefits due to strict language requirements are now eligible for review.
Despite ongoing research, no new evidence links herbicides to diseases.
Dr. Tollerud remains optimistic about future findings.
In Vietnam, the effects of Agent Orange persist, with many suffering from illnesses and birth defects.
Efforts are underway to support and care for those affected, highlighting the ongoing impact of this tragic chapter in history.
